{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/install-and-configure-opencv-4-2-0-in-windows-10-python-7a7386ae024", "time": 1683006061.963658, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/install-and-configure-opencv-4-2-0-in-windows-10-python-7a7386ae024/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "Install and configure OpenCV-4.2.0 in Windows 10 \u2014 Python | by Aymane Hachcham | Towards Data Science", "h1": "Install and configure OpenCV-4.2.0 in Windows 10 \u2014 Python", "description": "This post will guide you through all the steps for installing and configuring OpenCV-4.2.0 in Windows 10 (64-bit) for python use inside the Anaconda environment. I will focus here on OpenCV for\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "https://medium.com/p/d132c52063a1/edit", "anchor_text": "here", "paragraph_index": 1}, {"url": "https://www.anaconda.com/distribution/", "anchor_text": "Anaconda", "paragraph_index": 2}, {"url": "https://www.python.org/downloads/windows/", "anchor_text": "Python 3.6.0", "paragraph_index": 2}, {"url": "https://opencv-python-tutroals.readthedocs.io/en/latest/py_tutorials/py_setup/py_setup_in_windows/py_setup_in_windows.html", "anchor_text": "OpenCV official guide", "paragraph_index": 12}], "all_paragraphs": ["This post will guide you through all the steps for installing and configuring OpenCV-4.2.0 in Windows 10 (64-bit) for python use inside the Anaconda environment.", "I will focus here on OpenCV for python 3.6.0+, my previous post for VC++ integration can be found here.", "Note: To follow along with the tutorial, I will assume that you already have Anaconda and Python 3.6.0 installed. If not, please feel free to install these tools before continuing to read further.", "The steps for installing OpenCV through Anaconda are pretty easy and straight forward. Don\u2019t forget to add Anaconda to your path, so you can easily access conda command from the prompt.", "opencv-env refers to the virtual environment name, you can name it as you like, but remember to pick a meaningful name.", "Note: if you use bash as your default terminal in windows, conda activate opencv-env might not work as expected. The reason for it is that bash is not, by default, properly configured to run anaconda scripts, so you may give it a workaround:", "2. Whenever you want to lunch your bash terminal add the following arguments: --login -i , therefore you will lunch your custom bash profile which has been granted access to conda scripts.", "Now your conda environment is activated and perfectly available.", "To use OpenCV you have to install some important packages that go alongside:", "pip install numpy scipy matplotlib scikit-learn", "And you should get the latest OpenCV version available in the python repo.", "And that\u2019s all, have fun with OpenCV.", "For more install information, visit the OpenCV official guide.", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "Data Scientist & ML Engineer | NLP enthusiast. Contact me: hachcham.ayman@gmail.com"], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2F7a7386ae024&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Finstall-and-configure-opencv-4-2-0-in-windows-10-python-7a7386ae024&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign up"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=login&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Finstall-and-configure-opencv-4-2-0-in-windows-10-python-7a7386ae024&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign In"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/?source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": ""}, {"url": "https://medium